			<font color="#464f62">Using style sheets to seperate content from appearance</font>
			<p style="padding:5px;">Using <u>style sheets</u> helps keep your websiteâ€™s content (HTML) separate from its design (CSS). This makes your code easier to manage, maintain, and scale. Hereâ€™s how CSS works to structure your pageâ€™s design.</p><img src="DIVIDER3.gif"><br><br>
<!-- INFO STUFF -->
<font color="#999fad" size="2" style="text-align:left;">(Important CSS Basics)</font><br><br>
<font color="#5f6677"  size="3.5"style="text-align:left;">Case Sensitivity</font><p>Browsers are not case-sensitive when interpreting style sheets, but itâ€™s a best practice to use consistent capitalization in your code.</p><br>

<font color="#5f6677"  size="3.5"style="text-align:left;">Punctuation</font><ul type="disc" style="text-align: left;">Every style declaration must:<li>Include a colon : between the property and its value.</li><li>End with a semicolon ;.</li></ul></p>

<font color="#5f6677"  size="3.5"style="text-align:left;">White Space</font><p>Extra spaces improve readability but do not affect functionality.<br><i>If a property value includes spaces (e.g., font-family), enclose it in quotes for clarity.</i></p><img src="GIF8.gif"><br><br>

<font color="#999fad" size="2" style="text-align:left;">Style Properties and Values</font><br><br>
<font color="#5f6677"  size="3.5"style="text-align:left;">Property Types</font><ul type="disc" style="text-align: left;"><li>Fonts</li><li>Colors & Backgrounds</li><li>Text</li><Boxes & Layout</li><li>Lists</li><Tag Classification</li></ul></p><br>

<font color="#5f6677"  size="3.5"style="text-align:left;">Value Types</font><br><img src="SAMPLECODE2.png" width="550"><br>

<font color="#5f6677"  size="3.5"style="text-align:left;">Display Types</font><ul type="disc" style="text-align: left;">The display property controls how elements are arranged:<li>Block Elements: Stack vertically (p, div)</li><li>Inline Elements: Flow horizontally (em, b)</li></ul></p>

<font color="#5f6677"  size="3.5"style="text-align:left;">Managing Style Sheets</font><p>CSS can cascade, meaning multiple styles may apply to an element. The cascading order determines priority:</p><ol type="i" style="text-align: left;"><li>Inline Styles (highest priority).</li><li>External/Embedded Stylesheets.</li><li>Browser Defaults (lowest priority).</li></ol><br>

<font color="#5f6677"  size="3.5" style="text-align: left;">CSS Syntax and Selectors</font><ul type="disc" style="text-align: left;">CSS rules consist of:<li><u>Selector:</u> Specifies which HTML element(s) to style.</li><li><u>Declaration Block:</u> Contains style properties and values inside {}.</li></ul></p>

<font color="#5f6677"  size="3.5"style="text-align:left;">Selector Types</font><ul type="disc" style="text-align: left;"><li><u>Element Selector:</u> Targets all elements of a specific type</li><br><li><u>ID Selector:</u> Targets a single unique element using #</li><br><li><u>Class Selector:</u> Targets elements using a class name, prefixed with .</li><br><li><u>Universal Selector:</u> Targets all elements on the page using *</li><br><li><u>Group Selector:</u> Applies the same styles to multiple elements</li><br><li><u>Attribute Selector:</u> Targets elements with a specific attribute</li></ul></p><br>

